---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { data, formatNumber, formatPercent } from "../../lib/site-data";

const baseline = data.compare.regimes.find((regime) => regime.regime === "baseline") ?? data.compare.regimes[0];
const broad = data.compare.regimes.find((regime) => regime.regime === "broad");
const conservative = data.compare.regimes.find((regime) => regime.regime === "conservative");
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Method | FrontierGraph"
  description="How FrontierGraph builds a concept graph of economics and ranks underexplored links."
>
  <main>
    <section class="page-hero">
      <span class="eyebrow">Method</span>
      <h1>One graph pipeline, one public default.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        AI extracts graph structure from paper text. Ontology construction, ranking, comparison, and duplicate cleanup are deterministic and inspectable.
      </p>
      <div class="button-row">
        <span class="field-pill">Default: {data.default_view.regime} {data.default_view.mapping}</span>
        <a class="button-secondary" href="/graph/">Open graph</a>
        <a class="button-tertiary" href="/compare/">Open compare</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <article class="content-panel summary-panel">
        <span class="eyebrow">Short version</span>
        <h2>FrontierGraph turns a published-paper corpus into a reusable concept map, then ranks the links that still look structurally incomplete.</h2>
        <p class="card-copy">
          The current public build uses <strong>{formatNumber(data.metrics.papers)}</strong> papers,
          <strong> {formatNumber(data.metrics.node_instances)}</strong> extracted node instances, and
          <strong> {formatNumber(data.metrics.edges)}</strong> extracted edges. The public surface defaults to
          <strong> {baseline.label} exploratory</strong> because it stays compact without giving up much exploratory coverage.
        </p>
        <div class="pill-row">
          <span class="field-pill">{formatPercent(baseline.soft_coverage)} exploratory coverage</span>
          <span class="field-pill">{formatNumber(baseline.head_count)} baseline head concepts</span>
          <span class="field-pill">{formatNumber(data.metrics.suppressed_candidate_count)} visible ranked links</span>
        </div>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="section method-stack">
      <details class="method-detail" open>
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Corpus</span>
            <strong>What enters the graph</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            The public build uses the current <strong>FWCI core150 + adjacent150</strong> source cut and its merged extraction corpus.
            That keeps the graph tied to a curated published-paper sample rather than a broad scrape.
          </p>
          <p>
            Each paper contributes a local graph built from title and abstract text, so the final product is assembled from many paper-level structures rather than one global embedding pass.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="method-detail">
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Extraction</span>
            <strong>What the model does, and where it stops</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            The model extracts paper-local nodes and edges only. Nodes carry study-local context where available, while edges retain directionality, relation type, claim status, and evidence-method metadata.
          </p>
          <p>
            AI stops there. Ranking, ontology comparison, and cleanup all happen in deterministic downstream layers.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="method-detail">
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Ontology</span>
            <strong>Why Baseline exploratory is the default</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            FrontierGraph keeps three support-gated ontology regimes visible. The public default is
            <strong> {baseline.label} exploratory</strong>, with <strong>{formatNumber(baseline.head_count)}</strong> head concepts and
            <strong> {formatPercent(baseline.soft_coverage)}</strong> exploratory coverage.
          </p>
          <div class="pill-row">
            {broad && <span class="field-pill">Broad: {formatNumber(broad.head_count)} heads</span>}
            <span class="field-pill">Baseline: {formatNumber(baseline.head_count)} heads</span>
            {conservative && <span class="field-pill">Conservative: {formatNumber(conservative.head_count)} heads</span>}
          </div>
          <p>
            “Strict” mappings keep only high-confidence concept identity. “Exploratory” mappings widen coverage by adding nearest-head assignments for product-facing navigation and ranking.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="method-detail">
        <summary>
          <span>
            <span class="eyebrow">Ranking and cleanup</span>
            <strong>How missing links become the public opportunity surface</strong>
          </span>
        </summary>
        <div class="method-body">
          <p>
            The ranker combines deterministic graph signals such as path support, gap bonus, motif completion, mediator structure, co-occurrence scarcity, and hub penalties.
          </p>
          <p>
            A second deterministic suppression layer cleans near-synonym loops on the public Baseline exploratory top slice, leaving <strong>{formatNumber(data.metrics.suppressed_candidate_count)}</strong> visible candidates after cleanup.
          </p>
          <div class="button-row">
            <a class="button-secondary" href="/opportunities/">See opportunities</a>
            <a class="button-tertiary" href="/compare/">Inspect regime comparison</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
